		<td><b>Re: Famiclone with only black and white color [Solved]</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />In case this comes up again, loss of color is usually the first symptom of the clock source being too fast or too slow. Most other things don't require the same precision of frequency.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>HardWareMan</b> [ Thu Oct 31, 2013 9:07 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Famiclone with only black and white color [Solved]</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Shake the quartz resonator can lead to internal damage and a change in his nominal frequency. The change in frequency leads to a change in color subcarrier frequency and the color decoder can not recognize the signal. The resulting image is black and white, even if in general it's OK. For example, quartz shake can be caused by a fall of console from a height.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


